<dl id="n08125w"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08125w">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08125w"> 125(w)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> knots metania (reverence) / curchy curchy, <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08125w"><li>FW 476.35 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n08125w">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n08125w">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n08125w">MS BL 47482b-63</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:005 <a name="rA1d" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rA1d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/r/rA1d.htm#n08125w">Draft: III&sect;3A.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">At the beginning and at the end of each prayer said by a monk [in the Eastern Orthodox Church) upon each knot or bead he makes the &ldquo;great reverence&rdquo; (<i>he megale metanoia</i>) &hellip; bending down to the ground, so that the recitation of the rosary is often known as a metania. <small> <a name="CECRA" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CECRA"><cite title="source">&ldquo;Coemgen&rdquo;, &ldquo;Rosary&rdquo; and &ldquo;Albigenses&rdquo;</cite></a> <cite a>Catholic Encyclopaedia</cite></a> (1911) XIII, &lsquo;Rosary&rsquo; 187b</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: An obsolete form of &lsquo;curtsy&rsquo; (see OED &lsquo;curtsy&rsquo;). </mm> </dd></dl>
